questiontext.text:
Example

Sketch the cubic \(P(x) = x^3-3x^2+4\).

Solution

In order to accurately sketch the cubic we begin by finding the points at which it crosses the \(x\) and \(y\) axes. To find the \(x\)-intercepts we need to find the roots of the given cubic. We are given no further information about the factors or roots of the cubic, so we begin by inspection.

We evaluate: \[\begin{align*} P(1) = 1^3 - 3(1)^2 + 4 = 2 \qquad \mbox{so } 1 \mbox{ is not a root.}\\ P(-1) = (-1)^3 - 3(-1)^2 + 4 = -1-3+4 = 0 \qquad \mbox{so } -1 \mbox{ is a root.}\end{align*}\] Therefore we can apply the Factor Theorem which tells us that if \(-1\) is a root of \(P(x) = 0\) then \(x+1\) is a factor of \(P(x)\). Hence \[ P(x) = (x+1) \cdot \: (\mbox{a quadratic}) \] In order to find the quadratic we perform polynomial division to obtain \[ \frac{x^3-3x^2+4}{x+1} = x^2-4x+4. \] In order to write P(x) in its fully factorised form we have to factorise the quadratic as well. Doing this we obtain \[ P(x) = (x+1)(x-2)^2, \] therefore the roots of \(P(x)\) are \(x = -1\) and \(x = 2\). Note that the root \(x = 2\) is repeated twice.

 

We now wish to find the \(y\)-intercept for the cubic, so we must evaluate \(P(0)\) (since the \(y\)-axis corresponds to when \(x=0\)). So, we have that \(P(0) = 4.\) Finally, notice that the coefficient of \(x^3\) is \(1\), so it is positive and therefore the cubic goes to \(+\infty\) as \(x\) increases.

We are now in a position to collect all of this information and sketch this graph.

As we can see, the curve crosses the \(x\)-axis at one point - corresponding to the root \(x=-1\). The curve then touches the \(x\)-axis when \(x = 2\) which corresponds to the repeated root that we found.
